Reflection, looking at code as data.

Reflection is the ability of your code, while it is running, to inspect classes, methods, fields, constructors, and annotations, and even to invoke them. It treats code itself as data you can examine and manipulate. Everything in reflection starts from a class object, and you can get one of these in three ways. You can call get-class on any instance. You can write the class name followed by dot-class, a class literal. Or you can look one up by its fully qualified name with class-dot-for-name, which is how a framework loads a class it only learns about at runtime.

Once you hold a class object, you can do a lot. You can list its methods, fields, and constructors, and you can invoke them. You can construct a fresh instance by getting the no-argument constructor and calling new-instance. You can look up a specific method and call invoke on it, passing the target object and the arguments. And, strikingly, you can reach private members: get a declared field, call set-accessible with true to bypass the private modifier, and then read or write it directly. That ability to bypass access control is powerful, and it is exactly what serialisers and dependency-injection frameworks rely on.

But reflection has real costs. It is slower than a direct method call, and it bypasses the compile-time type checks that normally protect you, so mistakes surface only at runtime. So reach for it only when you genuinely must operate on code you do not know about until runtime: a framework processing classes supplied by the user, a serialiser inspecting arbitrary fields, or a test runner discovering test methods. For ordinary application logic, call methods directly.
